HEADWORD: Sate
<hw>Sate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Sated</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Probably shortened fr.
<ets>satiate</ets>: cf. L. <ets>satur</ets> full. See
<er>Satiate</er>.]</ety> <def>To satisfy the desire or appetite of; to
satiate; to glut; to surfeit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Crowds of wanderers <qex>sated</qex> with the business and
pleasure of great cities.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sate</ent>⟦br⟧

